# =============================================================================
#  DAY 6 CHALLENGE — SUGGESTED ANSWERS
#  (Teacher Reference — Not for student distribution before the activity!)
#
#  These are SUGGESTED answers — not the only right answers!
#  The goal of this activity is for students to discuss WHY they chose
#  each background, not to match this answer key exactly.
#
#  Great discussion questions:
#    "Why did you pick that background for Scene 3?"
#    "What would change if you used park_day instead of storm for Scene 4?"
#    "Did anyone pick the 'wrong' background on purpose? What happened?"
# =============================================================================

# SCENE 1 — Maya finds out she made the team
# SUGGESTED: park_day with dissolve  (bright, hopeful, exciting)
# ALSO WORKS: cafeteria (public announcement, social energy)
# INTERESTING CHOICE: classroom (ordinary setting makes the moment feel MORE surprising)

#   scene park_day with dissolve


# SCENE 2 — Maya tells Kai about Fridays
# SUGGESTED: hallway with dissolve  (private, awkward, heavy)
# ALSO WORKS: park_night (quiet, the weight of change)
# INTERESTING CHOICE: cafeteria (surrounded by noise makes their silence louder)

#   scene hallway with dissolve


# SCENE 3 — Bad first practice, embarrassment
# SUGGESTED: storm with fade  (heavy gray + dramatic black fade = crushing)
# ALSO WORKS: hallway with fade
# INTERESTING CHOICE: cafeteria with fade (the contrast of cheerful surroundings
#   and her embarrassment creates an ironic, uncomfortable mood)

#   scene storm with fade


# SCENE 4 — Late night, Maya considers quitting
# SUGGESTED: park_night with dissolve  (alone, dark, quiet)
# ALSO WORKS: hallway (closed in, trapped feeling)
# INTERESTING CHOICE: library (cozy but isolated — she's hiding from herself)

#   scene park_night with dissolve


# SCENE 5 — Kai's pep talk, turning point
# SUGGESTED: park_day with dissolve  (green = hope returning)
# ALSO WORKS: cafeteria (warmth, back among people, things are okay)
# INTERESTING CHOICE: library (thoughtful, determined, not celebratory yet —
#   more of a quiet resolve than a triumphant moment)

#   scene park_day with dissolve


# =============================================================================
#  TEACHER NOTES
# =============================================================================

# The most valuable moment in this activity is when students compare choices.
# Try having 2-3 students share their Scene 4 answer — the contrast between
# park_night (lonely), storm (frightened), and library (hiding/thinking) opens
# up a natural discussion about how mood isn't a single "right answer."
#
# The "interesting choice" options above are great to introduce AFTER students
# have shared their own work. They show that sometimes the unexpected background
# is a deliberate storytelling tool — not a mistake.
#
# If a student chose the "wrong" background and it produced an interesting
# effect, spotlight that! "Tell us why you picked that. What did you want
# the player to feel?" That metacognitive moment is the whole lesson.
